Data set

To determine countries that where worth investing in, we create a dataset with datas from FAO, WTO, European Union This part of the job was done with python.

We choose datas :

  • that describe the country:

    • population

    • GDP per capita

    • share of urban population

  • that show its economics stability

    • Currency volatility

    • food price volatility

    • logistic score

    • number of days to start a business

  • that indicate its involvement in global poultry meat trade

    • propensity to import

    • average duty (frozen cut meat)

  • that give indication concerning the poultry meat consumption

    • domestic aviability

    • poultry share in meat consumption

data<-read.table("data/dataset_P9.csv", header=T, sep=',', encoding='utf-8')
data <- subset(data, data$Country!='Venezuela, Bolivarian Republic of') # removed as it is a big outlier

rownames(data)<-data$Country
data$Country<- NULL
data$X<-NULL
data2 <-data[2:(length(data)-1)]

We get a dataset of 161 countries with 11 quantitative variables.

Correlations

pairs(data2[,1:11])

Graphicaly we see that some of this variables seems to be correlated. We need to build the correlation matrix.

corr.matrix<- cor(data2[,1:11])
corrplot(corr.matrix, method = "number", tl.cex=0.5,number.cex=0.7, type="lower")

We can see some good correlation between some variables (share of poultry in meat consumption with aviabale quantity per capita or logistic score and urban population with GDP per capita). But is it sufficient to run an PCA?

As the determinant of correlation matrix ( 0.031456 ) is different from 1 we can say that we do not work with an identity matrix. According to bartlett test, as p-value is 2.0340422^{-80}, our matrix is significantly different from identity matrix and we can start to work on a PCA.

KMO(corr.matrix)
## Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin factor adequacy
## Call: KMO(r = corr.matrix)
## Overall MSA =  0.63
## MSA for each item =

##                    GDP_per_capita               currency.volatility 
##                              0.68                              0.63 
## poultry_share_in_meat_consumption                share_of_urban_pop 
##                              0.44                              0.80 
##                    logistic.score       nb.days.to.start.a.business 
##                              0.66                              0.71 
##             food_price_volatility 
##                              0.70

The MSA indicator (>0,6) is not excellent on our matrix but still we can sum up data. The worsening indicator is poultry share in meat consumption but as it is quite highly correlated with avaibility per capita we should keep it.

PCA

res.PCA <-PCA(data2, scale.unit = TRUE, ncp = 6, graph = F)
eig.value <- get_eigenvalue(res.PCA)

fviz_eig(res.PCA, addlabels = TRUE, ylim = c(0, 50))

If we keep only eigen values > 1, we would explain 64% inertia with 4 dimensions. This is not much. If we want to explain more than 80% of inertia we should keep 6 dimensions.

If we try to interpret dimensions, we should have a look at variable contributions to dimensions.

  • dimensions 1 can be seen as a indicator of country development

First dimension seems really interesting for our purpose. Countries high on this axis will have a good revenu per habitant with a high population density, a good logistic score and propensity to import with low duties and good economic stability which could mean an easy and cheap access to solvent customers .

fviz_contrib(res.PCA, choice = "var", axes = 1, top = 10)

Hierarchical Clustering on Principal Components

res.hcpc <- HCPC(res.PCA,nb.clust=4,graph = FALSE)

fviz_dend(res.hcpc, 
          cex = 0.4,                    
          palette = "jco",               
          rect = TRUE, rect_fill = TRUE, 
          rect_border = "jco",           
          labels_track_height = 0.5      
          )

fviz_cluster(res.hcpc,
             repel = TRUE,            
             show.clust.cent = TRUE, #show cluster center
             palette = "jco",         
             ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
             main = "CAH clusters"
             )

With this classification we find 3 relevant clusters that we can sum up as developed countries, emerging countries and developing countries.

If we drop cluster 1 as it is only concerning Zimbabwe, we see that :

  • cluster 2 (developing countries) is most influence by the 2 first dimensions more specifically and by food price volatility (dim5). This cluster gathers countries with low GDP per capita, logistic score, share of urban population (dim1), available quantity per capita (dim1&2), poultry share in meat consumption (dim2) and domestic availability (dim3)

  • cluster 3 (emerging countries) is mostly influence per dimension 2

  • cluster 4 (developed countries) is well represented on dimensions 1, 3 and 2.

With this classification method, we could discard cluster 1 and 2. We, then can focus on countries like France (cluster 4) or countries a bite further with a least developed economy but a seems to be good poultry market. Before we go further down the analyse, lets check which result we get with an other classification method.

Looking at cluster 3 (~emerging countries ) and 4 ( ~ developed countries) we can reduce our dataset from 161 countries to 85 : 46 for cluster 3 and 39 for cluster 4.

Before going further in our analysis, some countries have to be ruled out for obvious reasons.

  • in cluster 3 :

  • Belarus, Russia and Ukraine currently at war cannot be considered as proper prospect.

  • Brazil as the prime poultry exportator should be considered as too challenging.

  • small islands (Antigua and Barbuda,Bahamas, Barbados) should ruled out too as transportation cost would be very high

C3$region <- rownames(C3)

df.C3<-subset(C3, C3$region!= "Belarus"&
         C3$region!="Russia"&
         C3$region!="Ukraine"&
         C3$region!="Antigua and Barbuda"&
         C3$region!="Bahamas"&
         C3$region!="Barbados"&
         C3$region!="Brazil"&
         C3$region!="Dominica"&

       C3$region!="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines"&
         C3$region!="Saint Lucia"&
       C3$region!="Trinidad and Tobago")

This reduce our C3 cluster to 34 countries.

  • in cluster 4 :

We should remove China and the USA as their market is to big to be considered as a whole.

C4$region <- rownames(C4)
df.C4 <- subset(C4, C4$region != "China"& C4$region != "Hong Kong, China" & C4$region!= "Macao, China" & C4$region!= "United States of America")

This reduce our fourth cluster to 34 observations.

Safe recommandation

df.C4<-df.C4[order(df.C4$GDP_per_capita, df.C4$share_of_urban_pop),]

heatmap(scale(df.C4[,1:11]),col= palette, Rowv=NA,Colv=NA, cexRow = 0.5, cexCol = 0.5)

If we are to export in country looking like France, we should look to countries with a good revenue per capita, eating and importing a lot of poultry, and with a high urban and logistic score so we can have a quick access to our customers. In the mean time, our target must be stable (currency and price) to limit our risk, with a low duties rate so we stay competitive and an easy settlement process is obviously a plus.

This means that we are looking for blue on the left side of the heatmap and orange on the right side.

Best candidates seem then to be:

  • Denmark

  • United Arab Emirates

  • The Netherlands (ruled out as a major importation hub)

a<-data[,c("global_population",'Influenza')]
a$region <- rownames(a)
subset(a, a$region=="United Arab Emirates"|a$region=="Denmark")
##                      global_population Influenza               region
## Denmark                       5752.126         1              Denmark

Denmark and United Arab Emirate offer reachable solvent market. Moreover both countries have experience aviary influenza this winter that can cause a call for air on their domestic market.
